Using the project rules in .cursorrules as your guide, implement the following.

## Task
Build the core Rive rendering hook that takes an AdSpec and applies all its slots
to a live Rive instance on a canvas.

## Files to create
1. src/types/ad-spec.schema.ts
2. src/lib/templateRegistry.ts
3. src/lib/riveApplier.ts
4. src/hooks/useAdSpecRenderer.ts
5. src/components/AdCanvas.tsx

---

## 1. src/types/ad-spec.schema.ts
Paste in the AdSpec schema exactly as defined in .cursorrules.
No changes to field names or types.

---

## 2. src/lib/templateRegistry.ts
A simple registry that maps template IDs to their .riv file paths.

export const TEMPLATE_REGISTRY: Record<string, string> = {
  'test-template': '/templates/test-template.riv',
  // future templates added here
};

export function getTemplatePath(templateId: string): string {
  const path = TEMPLATE_REGISTRY[templateId];
  if (!path) throw new Error(`Unknown template ID: "${templateId}"`);
  return path;
}

---

## 3. src/lib/riveApplier.ts
A pure utility — no React, no hooks. Takes a live Rive instance and an AdSpec,
and applies all slots to it. Called after the Rive onLoad fires.

import { Rive, decodeImage, decodeFont } from '@rive-app/canvas';
import type { AdSpec } from '../types/ad-spec.schema';

export async function applyAdSpec(rive: Rive, spec: AdSpec): Promise<void>

Implement in this order:
1. TEXT — iterate spec.text, call setTextRunValue for each defined slot.
   Use the slot key uppercased as the run name: e.g. headline → "TEXT_HEADLINE".
   Also apply spec.text.custom if present.

2. STATE MACHINE INPUTS — get inputs via rive.stateMachineInputs(spec.template.stateMachine).
   Apply spec.stateInputs.speed, intensity as number inputs by name.
   Apply spec.stateInputs.mood as a boolean input: find input named `mood_${spec.stateInputs.mood}` and set to true.
   Apply spec.stateInputs.custom entries by name.
   Gracefully skip any input that doesn't exist in the SM (no throw — just console.warn).

3. COLORS — not handled in this file. Add a comment:
   // COLOR SLOTS: applied via low-level API in a separate colorApplier.ts (future task)

4. ASSETS — not handled in this hook. Add a comment:
   // ASSET SLOTS: applied via assetLoader callback at Rive instantiation time (future task)

---

## 4. src/hooks/useAdSpecRenderer.ts
A React hook. Signature:

import type { AdSpec } from '../types/ad-spec.schema';
import type { RefObject } from 'react';

interface UseAdSpecRendererResult {
  isLoading: boolean;
  error: Error | null;
  riveInstance: Rive | null;
}

export function useAdSpecRenderer(
  spec: AdSpec | null,
  canvasRef: RefObject<HTMLCanvasElement>
): UseAdSpecRendererResult

Implementation notes:
- Use @rive-app/canvas (not the advanced package — colors come later).
- Use useRive from @rive-app/react-canvas is NOT appropriate here because we need
  manual control over when applyAdSpec fires. Instantiate Rive directly.
- On mount (or when spec changes): instantiate Rive with src from getTemplatePath,
  artboard and stateMachine from spec.template, autoplay: true.
- In onLoad callback: call resizeDrawingSurfaceToCanvas(), then call applyAdSpec(riveInstance, spec).
  applyAdSpec is async — handle its promise with .catch(setError).
- On unmount or spec change: call riveInstance.cleanup() to prevent WASM memory leaks.
- Manage isLoading (true until onLoad fires) and error state.
- If spec is null, return { isLoading: false, error: null, riveInstance: null } immediately.

---

## 5. src/components/AdCanvas.tsx
A thin wrapper component. Renders a <canvas> and wires it to the hook.

Props:
interface AdCanvasProps {
  spec: AdSpec;
  width: number;
  height: number;
  className?: string;
}

- Create a canvasRef with useRef<HTMLCanvasElement>(null).
- Call useAdSpecRenderer(spec, canvasRef).
- Render a relative-positioned div wrapper containing:
  - The <canvas ref={canvasRef} width={width} height={height} />
  - If isLoading: a centered loading indicator (simple text "Generating..." is fine for now)
  - If error: a centered error message showing error.message

---

## Acceptance criteria
- Zero TypeScript errors in strict mode.
- Rive instance is always cleaned up on unmount.
- applyAdSpec never throws — only console.warns on missing SM inputs.
- No hardcoded template paths outside templateRegistry.ts.
- Each file is under 200 lines.

